<div>

    <p>

        SUMMARY/REPORT

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Case Study : How Can a Wellness Technology Company Play It Smart?

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        #About The Company

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        “Bellabeat” , a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for

        women was founded in 2013 by Urška Sršen and Sando Mur.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Sršen developed and  designed technology that informs and inspires women

        around the world by collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and

        reproductive health which empower women with knowledge about their own

        health and habits. By 2016, Bellabeat had opened offices around the

        world and launched multiple products.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Key-highlights:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        #Products offered by Bellabeat:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        1) Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data

        related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and

        mindfulness habits. This data can help users better understand their

        current habits and make healthy decisions. The Bellabeat app connects to

        their line of smart wellness products.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        2) Leaf: Bellabeat’s classic wellness tracker can be worn as a bracelet,

        necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat app to

        track activity, sleep, and stress.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        3) Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic

        timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and

        stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide you with

        insights into your daily wellness.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        4) Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake using

        smart technology to ensure that you are appropriately hydrated

        throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to

        track your hydration levels.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        5) Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also offers a subscription-based

        membership program for users. Membership gives users           24/7

        access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep,

        health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        #Business Goal:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Analysis of Bellabeat’s available consumer data to reveal more

        opportunities for growth.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        #Deliverables:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        1) A clear summary of the business task

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        2) A description of all data sources used

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        3) Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        4) A summary of analysis

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        5) Supporting visualizations and key findings

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        6) Top high-level content recommendations based on analysis

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        1)Business Task:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        To analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how

        consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices, in this case “Fitbit” data.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

    </div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    What are some trends in smart device usage?

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing

                    strategy?

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <p>

            2) Data Sources:

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Link to data:

                    <a

                        href="https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit"

                        target="_blank"

                        rel="noreferrer noopener"

                    >

                        https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit

                    </a>

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    This is a Public Domain, dataset made available through

                    Mobius: This Kaggle data set contains personal fitness

                    tracker from 33 Fitbit users. 33 eligible Fitbit users

                    consented to the submission of personal tracker data,

                    including minute-level output for physical activity, heart

                    rate, and sleep monitoring. It includes information about

                    daily activity, steps, and heart rate that can be used to

                    explore users’ habits.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    The dataset was originally generated by respondents through

                    a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    The survey spanned a 30 day period starting April 12th, 2016

                    to May 12th, 2016.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Note: This data set have some limitations, adding another data to it

            help address those limitations as we begin to work more with this

            data.

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Limitations:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        This data is not representative of all Fitbit users as only 33 people

        took part in the survey.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        The largest table in the provided data is dailyActivity_merged.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Roughly one fourth participant didn’t record sleep data, and almost

        three fourth participants didn’t record weight data.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Few records are missing as the participants were not asked to wear the

        Fitbit gadget for entirety of 30 day period.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        This data is old as it was surveyd in 2016. The data comes from third

        party so there is no way to examine the data credibility and any

        potential biases.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        3) Documentation of cleaning, manipulation and analysis of data:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        I have done the data cleaning, manipulation and analysis for this case

        study in SQL server (Bigquery console).

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        Here is the link to SQL query/code script:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        <a

            href="https://console.cloud.google.com/bigquery?sq=1035602808525:c5b9079fb24e413eaf0e932edb94a07a"

            target="_blank"

            rel="noreferrer noopener"

        >

            https://console.cloud.google.com/bigquery?sq=1035602808525:c5b9079fb24e413eaf0e932edb94a07a

        </a>

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        The tables I have analyzed from this dataset are following:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        dailyActivity_merged, sleeplog_merged and weightLogInfo_merged, which

        were renamed and cleaned before performing analysis.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <p>

            The reason to choose these 3 tables in this case study is, the

            insufficient data in other tables.

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Participants in this study collected far more activity data than

            data on sleep or weight.

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Cleaning Steps:

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Consistency: I identified the standard character length for

                    each user ID (10). Across all tables, there were no

                    deviations from this and/or incorrect inputs.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Find unique participants by examining the Ids in all three

                    tables. ( 33 unique IDs found in daily_activity table, 24

                    unique IDs found in sleep_log table, 8 unique IDs found in

                    weight_info table)

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Converted data type: converted Boolean values in

                    IsManualReport column in weight_info table to string "True"

                    and "False"

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Duplicates: I found and deleted 3 duplicate rows total, all

                    in the sleep log table

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Creating a new column:  From ActivityDate column to get

                    corresponding days of the week to identify if the date falls

                    under weekdays or weekends category.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Misleading records: 77 records in the dataset reported a

                    total of zero daily steps. While technically possible that

                    these records reflect days that participants were wholly

                    inactive—most of the same records also claim 24 hours of

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    sedentary activity—they’re more likely reflective of days

                    the users didn’t wear their FitBits, making the values

                    potentially misleading. As a result, these 77 records were

                    deleted from the dataset.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        4) &amp; 5)  Summary Of Analysis and supporting Visualization :

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        FitBit/Bellabeat users use this device data to improve their health, so

        it makes sense to analyze and identify the healthy and unhealthy

        tendencies shown in the data. Primarily, I’ll be looking at sleep,

        calories, and steps/activity data.

    </p>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        A) Sleep Analysis:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <p>

        1) Missing sleep records: The data was aggregated by week of the day to

        understand the sleeping patterns on weekly basis. Its clear from the

        chart that majority of people forgot to record the sleep log on Tuesday

        and Wednesday.

    </p>

</div>

</div>

        guidelines, 7 hours is the recommended sleep a person needs in a day. As

        per the chart its clear that on mostly Mondays (26 days) and Tuesdays

        (28 days) people get 7 hours of sleep.

    </p>

    </p>

    <p>

        6) Top high-level content recommendations based on analysis:

    </p>

</div>

<div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Below are some recommendations to the marketing team for curating

            their marketing strategies based on my understanding after the data

            analysis.

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Observations and Trends:

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    More steps means more calories burned.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Most users walk about 5K to 10K steps on average in a day.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Sundays are preferred for sleeping/taking rest having least

                    activity.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Saturdays are preferred for the longest walks or most number

                    of steps taken while also catching up on sleep.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    People on average spend more than half of their time as

                    sedentary time, probably because they are seated for their

                    desk jobs.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    To improve quality and duration of sleep, they should reduce

                    their sedentary time and be more physically active.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    People tend to go for highest intensity runs/walks and

                    workouts on tuesdays and that keeps reducing till weekends

                    as people get busy with their work throughout the week.

                    Saturdays see a little rise while Sundays being the least as

                    it's preferred as a rest day.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

    <div>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <p>

            Recommendations:

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    People in long sedentary/seated positions can be reminded of

                    taking a walk around every hour with pop-ups/reminders in

                    their smart devices.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Send reminders/notifications on device everyday for users to

                    stick to sleep routine and sleep at least 6-8 hrs everyday.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Highlight the benefits of a proper daily sleep with tips,

                    small reads and articles. Direct and inspire people to use

                    more of their sleep tracker in the devices.

                </p>

            </li>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Create personalized challenges/goals like taking 5K steps,

                    then 8K steps, sleeping 8 hrs, on time, walking everyday and

                    such.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>

    </div>

</div>

<div>

    <div>

        <ul>

            <li>

                <p>

                    Marketing Campaigns and Tie ups with gyms and fitness clubs

                    to focus on the right user groups, who are interested in

                    getting fit. The memberships can be clubbed with device

                    costs which will also provide huge sets of data from

                    different types of users, unfit to fit, over periods of

                    time, for further exploration.

                </p>

            </li>

        </ul>
